{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657420"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:28:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.72,0.05,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12358"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70287"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6884"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29514"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe oesophagus begins at the level of the cricoid cartilage (C6) and descends through the posterior mediastinum. It passes through the oesophageal hiatus of the diaphragm, which is formed by the muscular right crus. Along its course, it relates to several important structures:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETrachea and its bifurcation (anterior)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELeft atrium and pericardium (anterior)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EArch of aorta and descending thoracic aorta (left then posterior)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERight mediastinal pleura\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EArch of azygos vein\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the vertebral level at which the oesophagus pierces the diaphragm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["T9 vertebral level","T10 vertebral level","T11 vertebral level","T12 vertebral level","L1 vertebral level"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe oesophagus pierces the diaphragm at the \u003Cstrong\u003ET10 vertebral level\u003C/strong\u003E. This can be remembered as \u0027oesophagus\u0027 has 10 letters, and it passes with the tenth cranial nerve (vagus).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent different vertebral levels:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET9 vertebral level\u003C/strong\u003E is above the oesophageal hiatus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET11 vertebral level\u003C/strong\u003E is below the oesophageal hiatus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET12 vertebral level\u003C/strong\u003E is where the aortic hiatus is located\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EL1 vertebral level\u003C/strong\u003E is below all major diaphragmatic apertures\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe three main diaphragmatic apertures occur at:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ET8 - Inferior vena cava (with phrenic nerve)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ET10 - Oesophagus (with vagus nerves)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ET12 - Aorta (with thoracic duct)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The oesophagus pierces the diaphragm at the level of the tenth thoracic vertebra (T10).","The oesophageal hiatus is formed by the right crus of the diaphragm and transmits both the oesophagus and vagus nerves.","The three main diaphragmatic apertures occur at T8 (inferior vena cava), T10 (oesophagus), and T12 (aorta)."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70287"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70287"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-18T22:34:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-18T22:35:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12358"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","nam